Forecasting Elections with Polls

Forecasting elections has been a pastime of politically savvy Americans ever since one can remember. After all, its a challenge that no one has yet to master this practice on a consistent, election-to-election basis there are simply too many changing variables (in terms of presence and weighting) each cycle.

Forecasting elections has become a favorite pastime of politically savvy Americans

Fundamentals - Typically the most reliable, non-polling factor accurate way to predict a race (538). Margin of victory in previous elections (adjusted for national political environment and opponent), generic congressional ballot, fundraising,

Weighting - (sample size, population proportion, pollster rating based on past accuracy, likely voter adjustment, timeline adjustment based on subsequent generic ballot changes for instance, house effects adjustment to correct historical pollster bias)

House models tend to be less polling centric (538) - with magnitude of House races/cycle, impossible to accurately predict which factors matter and by how much in each districts race. Polling is sparse and unreliable from district to district, but if high-quality polls arise, they should be factored in as they are a direct measure of the people. Also need to take into account if it is a partisan poll as well (538)
